  "prompt": "What are div1 and div2 on topcoder?",
  "response": "On Topcoder, \"div1\" and \"div2\" refer to divisions of competition based on the rating of the competitor. They're used primarily in Single Round Matches (SRMs) to group coders with similar skill levels together for fairer competition.\n\n*   **Division 1 (div1):** This division is for more experienced and highly rated coders. Typically, competitors with a Topcoder rating of **1200 or higher** participate in Division 1. The problems in div1 SRMs are generally more difficult and require more sophisticated algorithms and data structures to solve.\n\n*   **Division 2 (div2):** This division is for less experienced or lower rated coders. Competitors with a Topcoder rating **below 1200** participate in Division 2. The problems in div2 SRMs are generally easier and designed to be solvable by those with a basic understanding of algorithms and data structures.\n\n**Key Differences and Implications:**\n\n*   **Problem Difficulty:** The main difference between div1 and div2 is the difficulty of the problems. div1 problems require deeper algorithmic knowledge and more creative problem-solving skills.\n*   **Coding Speed:** Because div1 problems are harder, you may need to code them slower and with more care compared to div2 problems.\n*   **Rating Impact:** Performance in a division has a direct impact on your Topcoder rating. Performing well in div1 results in a higher rating increase than performing well in div2.  Similarly, performing poorly has a bigger negative impact in div1.\n*   **Competition:** You are competing against other participants within your division. This means your relative performance compared to other competitors within your division determines your rating change.\n*   **Problem Set:** Both divisions are in the same round. All coders read all problems. However, during coding and challenge phase you are in your divison.\n\n**In Summary:**\n\ndiv1 and div2 are rating-based divisions on Topcoder used in SRMs to provide a more level playing field for competitors with different skill levels. div1 is for higher-rated, more experienced coders, while div2 is for lower-rated, less experienced coders. The problem difficulty and rating impact are significantly different between the two divisions.\n",
